I think having access to a borrowing library is one of the best parts of working at FSU, and the fact that it's part of the minuteman library network means that I can get almost any book I want... eventually. I really appreciate the library staff, I know they are doing the best they can with the funding that they have. But my experience in using the library as an actual library (a place to get books to read) has been very disappointing. In my five years at FSU, I have NEVER walked into the Whittemore library looking for a book (here are some of the books I have tried to find: the Martian, Asimov's Foundation, any of the works of Kurt Vonnegut, any play by Tom Stoppard) and successfully walked out with that book. The physical collection is very weak, the books you do have are usually very old editions, the collection is not updated, and it seems that when books go missing they do not get replaced. It seems that the only circulating collection that is well-maintained is children's and young adult literature. Think about the message this sends about the perceived intellectual capabilities of this community. The other problem is that the front desk is staffed by students who do not seem to know much about books, or even how to use the Dewey Decimal system. I have learned to stop asking them for help, but it is also not very easy to help myself even though I am a former public library employee and I understand the Dewey Decimal system (although all modern libraries use Library of Congress now, come on!). The "catalog computers" that we can use to look up books are so slow that a card catalog would be faster, but there isn't one of those either. In modern libraries, the catalog computers do not require you to log on, and are always open to the catalog search page. Basically all these experiences have made it clear to me that the expectation for this community is that we do not want to read books. I think that is a very bad message at an institution of higher learning.

Some of my answers I may have indicated lower due to the fact that occasionally student workers are providing the service and may not have the expertise that a full-time employee may have.  Overall, I am very happy with the library and the technology supported to me.

ITS Ticket and Service Desk is extremely helpful just tough to do on-line help sometimes during the pandemic.  Reimaging a laptop which requires 24 hours without your laptop is tough for me personally but ITS had helped me significantly this Covid period with various IT issues.  My laptop has had many many problems!  (not user-based ;)  I would recommend at some point that a new laptop is ordered when the same problems occur time and again even after re-imaging.  I know this might be a budget issue but my laptop has gone in for reimaging, is good for some months, then the old problems come back.  Not finding Wifi networks etc.  Just my two cents.  But I cannot say enough about the patience of the ITS staff in helping me out.
